A '''high forest''' is a type of [[forest]] originated from seed or from planted seedlings. In contrast to a low forest<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionaryofforestry.org/dict/term/low_forest|title=SAFnet Dictionary - Definition For [low_forest]|publisher=|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130712035805/http://dictionaryofforestry.org/dict/term/low_forest|archivedate=2013-07-12|df=}}</ref> (also known as a [[Coppicing|coppice forest]]), a high forest usually consists of large, tall mature trees with a closed canopy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dictionary of Forestry|url=http://dictionaryofforestry.org/dict/term/high_forest|work=Society of American Foresters|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709223800/http://dictionaryofforestry.org/dict/term/high_forest|archivedate=2013-07-09|df=}}</ref> High forests can occur naturally or they can be created and/or maintained by human management. Trees in a high forest can be of one, a few or many species. A high forest can be [[Even-aged timber management|even-aged]] or uneven-aged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionaryofforestry.org/dict/term/uneven-aged_system|title=SAFnet Dictionary - Definition For [uneven-aged_system]|publisher=|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227204847/http://dictionaryofforestry.org/dict/term/uneven-aged_system|archivedate=2013-12-27|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Smith|first=D.M.|title=The Practice of Silviculture|year=1986|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|location=New York|pages=527}}</ref> Even-aged forests contain trees of one, or two successional age classes (generations). Uneven-aged forests have three or more age classes represented.
High forests have relatively high [[genetic diversity]] compared with coppice forests, which develop from [[vegetative reproduction]]. A high forest can have one or more [[Canopy (biology)#Canopy layer of forests|canopy layers]]. The [[understory]] of a high forest can be open (parklike, easy to see and walk through), or it can be dense. A high forest's understory can have high or low vegetation [[species diversity]].
