'''Lightglove''' is a brand of [[human interface device]] that uses light to create a virtual glove, detecting finger and wrist motion.<ref name="CNBC">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/22274276/ |accessdate=21 July 2009 |title=Bruce & MG Howard, Lightglove Biography - The Big Idea: Road to CES - CNBC.com |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080823215335/http://www.cnbc.com/id/22274276 |archivedate=23 August 2008 |df= }}</ref> Worn on the underside of the wrist, a ''Lightglove'' can be used as a computer mouse, gaming controller or remote control.

The product was shown at the 2009 [[World Technology Summit]]<ref name="WTN">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtn.net/summit2009/nominees.html|accessdate=21 July 2009|title=The World Technology Summit & Awards 2009}}</ref> and the 2008 [[Consumer Electronics Show]].<ref name="CNET">{{cite web|url=http://ces.cnet.com/1991-19167_1-6948642-1.html|accessdate=21 July 2009|title=CES 2009 - Consumer Electronics Show - CNET.com}}</ref> At the 2008 Consumer Electronics Show (CES), the product won the ''Best of Innovation for Electronic Gaming'' award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cesweb.org/awards/innovations/2008honorees.asp?category=896058 |title=2010 CES: 2008 Innovations Honorees |publisher=Cesweb.org |date= |accessdate=2009-10-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613041719/http://cesweb.org/awards/innovations/2008honorees.asp?category=896058 |archivedate=2010-06-13 |df= }}</ref>

