[[File:Retiarius vs secutor from Borghese mosaic.jpg|thumb|[[Retiarius]] vs [[Secutor]], the two gladiators lying are dead, as signified by the ''theta nigrum'']] The '''theta nigrum''' ("black [[theta]]") or '''theta infelix''' ("unlucky theta") is a [[Symbols of death|symbol of death]] in Greek and Latin [[epigraphy]].<ref name="Mednik">{{cite journal |last=Mednikarova |first=Iveta |last2= |first2= |date= |title=The Use of Θ in Latin Funerary Inscriptions |url= |journal=Zeitschrift für Papyrologie und Epigraphik|volume=136 |issue=|pages=267–276 |doi= |access-date=2017-03-23}}</ref> [[Isidore of Seville]] notes the letter was appended after the name of a deceased soldier and finds of [[papyrus|papyri]] containing military records have confirmed this use.<ref name="Mednik" /> Additionally it can be seen in [[Gladiator Mosaic|The Gladiator Mosaic]].
The term ''theta nigrum'' was coined by [[Theodor Mommsen]], but It consists of a circle with a diagonal line. The ''Theta'' signified [[Thanatos]], the Greek deity of death.<ref>[https://books.google.de/books?id=Mt9FAQAAMAAJ&hl=de&pg=PA229#v=onepage&q=Theta&f=false A Dictionary of Latin Phrases]</ref>
